function encodeString(str) {
    return btoa(unescape(encodeURIComponent(str)));
}

function decodeString(encodedStr) {
    return decodeURIComponent(escape(atob(encodedStr)));
}

const originalString = "This is a very long string that needs to be encoded";
const encodedString = encodeString(originalString);
console.log(encodedString);

const decodedString = decodeString(encodedString);
console.log(decodedString);
```

In this example, the `encodeString` function uses `encodeURIComponent` to escape special characters, `unescape` to convert escaped characters to their original form, and `btoa` to convert the string to Base64.

The `decodeString` function does the reverse: it uses `atob` to convert the Base64 string back to a regular string, `escape` to convert escaped characters back to their original form, and `decodeURIComponent` to unescape special characters.

Note that Base64 encoding will increase the length of your string, so you may want to consider using a more compact encoding scheme like URL-safe hexadecimal encoding if you're concerned about the length of the encoded string. However, Base64 is a widely supported and easy-to-implement encoding scheme, so it's often a good choice for simple encoding needs.

